			<h2>Demonstrative Pronouns</h2>
			<p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">D</span>emonstrative Pronouns are words which indicate
				specific items. We have already seen demonstratives used to mean ‘the’ with our strong nouns, but
				‘<em>se</em>’, ‘<em>þæt</em>’ and ‘<em>seo</em>’ can also mean ‘that’. In fact, it should be obvious
				that the modern word ‘that’ comes from the neuter demonstrative ‘<em>þæt</em>’.</p>
			<p>
				Examine the sentences below. The translation ‘that sheep is bigger and that sheep is smaller’ makes
				a lot more sense than ‘the sheep is bigger and the sheep is smaller’, so it is important to realise
				that a '<em>se</em>' demonstrative might either mean 'the' or 'that' depending on context, even though
				we have been using them for ‘the’ up until now.
			</p>
